snippet.textDisplay:
This was our last video for the year 12019 of the Human Era. And what a year it was. So much stuff happened everywhere. To so many different people.
Calendars and holidays are just imaginary but they help us to cut our lives into pieces that our brains can handle.
We are leaving 12019 behind with a weird mixture of disillusion and hope. The world is screwed up. But we can fix it. In a few days this year will be over. And we all get to try again.
Thank you for watching our videos and for sticking around for so many years. See you all in 12020.

snippet.textDisplay: We should be able to make a sphere thruster with variable shutters or deflection plates that ensures the planets don’t get roasted.  This would give us a full range of motion.  Working with or enhancing the electromagnetic field could be of value.  A higher order might focus all the energy and directing it where needed to avoid waist.  Beyond thrust and Earth getting a proper amount of radiation, Mercury could get less, and Europa more if so desired.  If you like the general concept for the small screen in mind, search Ori warship.  The warship has a star at the center used for both propulsion and as a weapon in the front.  If we were moving our solar system in a new direction, having a directed beam to destroy threats in our path would be of value.

snippet.textDisplay: Caplan Thruster does not use any bracket to fix on the sun. On the one hand, it uses the nuclear fusion engine to emit oxygen for thrust, and on the other hand, it uses the electromagnetic engine to accelerate the hydrogen to be ejected in the opposite direction to maintain the distance from the sun. There is no point of contact with the sun, and thrust in opposite directions will only propel the engine forward and backward, either falling into the sun and burning away, or away from the sun. How can it push the entire solar system forward?
